{
    "node_id": "time-matrix-19",
    "title": "The Choice: Active or Passive?",
    "description": "Learning when to focus on the person (Active) or the object (Passive).",
    "display_order": 19,
    "prerequisites": ["time-matrix-18"],
    "lesson_content_markdown": "# The Choice: Active or Passive?\n\nIn academic writing, you must choose whether to focus on the **person** (the researcher) or the **object** (the research). This is the difference between Active and Passive.\n\n### 1. Focus on the Person (Active)\nUse the active voice when the person is the most important part of the sentence.\n- **Example**: The professor **tests** the students. (Focus on the professor.)\n- **Example**: Researchers **found** a new way to clean the water.\n\n### 2. Focus on the Object (Passive)\nUse the passive voice when the action or the result is more important than the person.\n- **Example**: The students **are tested**. (Focus on the students.)\n- **Example**: A new way to clean the water **was found**. (The discovery is more important!)\n\n### 3. Making the Decision\n- **Scientific Reports**: Usually Passive (*\"The sample is heated\"*).\n- **General Stories**: Usually Active (*\"The student heated the sample\"*).\n- **The \"By\" Phrase**: If we still want to say who did it, we use \"by\".\n- **Example**: The email **was sent by** the office manager.\n\n---",
